{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528411"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:42:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:42:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14300"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14300"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.27,0.63,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6995"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107588"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6995"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14300"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90040"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"1779"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16557"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17595"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38098"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39673"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43517"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44604"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107588"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic for her routine 20-week anatomy scan. She is gravida 3, para 2, with two previous cesarean deliveries. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The ultrasound reveals a low-lying placenta covering the internal cervical os. The sonographer notes irregular placental lacunae and loss of the clear space between the placenta and myometrium.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most clinically significant diagnosis in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Placental abruption","Placenta praevia","Placenta accreta","Circumvallate placenta","Vasa praevia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most clinically significant diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eplacenta accreta\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is characterised by abnormal placental attachment to the myometrium, where the placenta invades beyond the decidua basalis. The ultrasound findings of irregular placental lacunae and loss of the clear space between the placenta and myometrium are highly suggestive of placenta accreta.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacenta praevia\u003C/strong\u003E is present in this case, as evidenced by the low-lying placenta covering the internal cervical os. However, this alone does not explain the abnormal placental attachment suggested by the ultrasound findings. Placenta praevia is a risk factor for placenta accreta, especially in women with previous cesarean deliveries. The management pathways for these conditions differ significantly - isolated placenta praevia typically requires follow-up ultrasound in the third trimester to assess if it has resolved, whereas suspected placenta accreta requires urgent referral to Maternal-Fetal Medicine specialists and possibly MRI for further evaluation due to the high risk of life-threatening haemorrhage at delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacental abruption\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the premature separation of the placenta from the uterine wall. It typically presents with vaginal bleeding and abdominal pain, which are not mentioned in this case. Ultrasound findings for placental abruption would include retroplacental clots or hematomas, which are not described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasa praevia\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition where fetal blood vessels from the placenta or umbilical cord cross the internal cervical os beneath the fetus. While it can be associated with a low-lying placenta, the specific ultrasound findings mentioned are not characteristic of vasa praevia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECircumvallate placenta\u003C/strong\u003E is an morphological abnormality where the chorionic plate is smaller than the basal plate, resulting in a raised placental margin. This condition would not typically present with the ultrasound findings described in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s history of two previous cesarean deliveries is a significant risk factor for placenta accreta. The combination of placenta praevia and previous cesarean deliveries increases the likelihood of abnormal placental invasion. Early diagnosis of placenta accreta is crucial for appropriate management and planning of delivery to reduce the risk of severe postpartum hemorrhage and other complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Placenta accreta is characterised by abnormal placental attachment to the myometrium.","Ultrasound is the primary imaging modality for diagnosing placenta accreta.","Risk factors for placenta accreta include previous cesarean delivery and placenta praevia."],"references":["Jauniaux ERM, Alfirevic Z, Bhide AG, Belfort MA, Burton GJ, Collins SL, Dornan S, Jurkovic D, Kayem G, Kingdom J, Silver R, Sentilhes L. Placenta praevia and placenta accreta: diagnosis and management. Green-top Guideline No. 27a. BJOG. 2018 Sep 27. doi: 10.1111/1471-0528.15306. Available at: https://www.rcog.org.uk/guidance/browse-all-guidance/green-top-guidelines/placenta-praevia-and-placenta-accreta-diagnosis-and-management-green-top-guideline-no-27a/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90040"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14300"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90040"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T09:59:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T10:00:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6995"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107588"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical stud